clautolisp-dialect-portability-warnings — verify the dialect portability-warning mechanism is implemented, with tests
====================================================================================================================

See also:
  - autolisp-spec/documentation/autolisp-visual-lisp-specification-draft.org
    chapter 25, "** Normative Rules: Dialect Portability Warnings" — the
    spec section defining the model this issue verifies against.
  - issues/open/autolisp-spec-defun-rest-parameter.issue — the first
    concrete construct (`defun` `&rest`) that must emit such a warning.
  - clautolisp/autolisp-reader/source/dialect.lisp — named dialects
    (:strict 101, :autocad-2026 104, :bricscad-v26 120, :clautolisp 133)
    and the dialect descriptor where a warning/escalation knob would live.
  - clautolisp/autolisp-runtime/source/api.lisp:2276 — the unbound-variable
    dialect-gated branch, as a model for where/how a dialect-gated
    diagnostic is dispatched at evaluation time.

Context
-------

The specification now defines *dialect portability warnings* (chapter 25):
advisory, run-time diagnostics printed when an executing program reaches a
construct unsupported by the host targeted by the active dialect. The
defining properties:

  - Run-time, evaluation-tied: a warning fires only when the incompatible
    construct is actually evaluated. Guarded/feature-tested code that is
    never reached produces no warning.
  - Once per occurrence: each distinct source occurrence warns at most
    once per run, on its first evaluation. A loop around an incompatible
    expression warns once, not once per iteration. A different occurrence
    (another defun, another call site) warns separately.
  - Advisory: evaluation is unchanged; under a dialect whose target host
    supports the construct natively, nothing is printed. Optional
    escalation to error is a separate knob (cf. :unbound-variable-mode
    :strict-error).
  - One knowledge base: the catalogue of "construct X unsupported by
    host/dialect Y" feeds both the run-time emitter and any static linter.

The user reports never having seen any such warning printed — so the first
job is to establish what, if anything, is currently implemented.

Scope of work
-------------

1. Audit current state. Determine whether ANY dialect portability warning
   is emitted today:
     - grep the reader/runtime for an existing warning emitter and a
       per-occurrence dedup table; identify whether the plumbing exists
       and is simply unused, or is absent.
     - confirm whether warnings are wired to the active dialect at all.
   Record findings so we know if this is "verify" or "build".

2. Define the warning infrastructure (if missing):
     - a portability knowledge base / catalogue mapping a construct
       (special form, function, or argument shape) -> the set of
       host/dialects that support it, with a human-readable message.
     - a once-per-occurrence dedup mechanism keyed by source occurrence
       (definition site or call site), reset per run/evaluation session,
       NOT keyed by construct class.
     - a dialect-gated emit point at evaluation time (mirror the
       unbound-variable dispatch at autolisp-runtime/source/api.lisp:2276):
       warn iff the active dialect's target host lacks the construct.
     - an optional warning->error escalation knob on the dialect
       descriptor, off by default (precedent: :unbound-variable-mode).

3. First concrete consumer: `defun` `&rest` (see the defun-rest issue).
     - Native under :bricscad-v26 and :clautolisp -> no warning.
     - Under :strict and :autocad-2026 -> warn once at the definition's
       first evaluation, message naming the function, e.g.
       "DIALECT WARNING: DEFUN FOO with &REST only works in bricscad and
       clautolisp".

4. Enumerate the other constructs that should warn. Walk chapter 24
   ("BricsCAD Extensions") and the cross-vendor hazards already recorded
   (e.g. anything BricsCAD-only) and build the initial catalogue. List
   them in this issue as they are confirmed; each entry needs the
   supporting host set and a message.

5. Tests (the core deliverable). For `&rest` first, then each catalogued
   construct:
     - fires once on first evaluation under :strict and :autocad-2026;
     - silent under :bricscad-v26 and :clautolisp;
     - a second distinct occurrence warns independently;
     - an occurrence evaluated repeatedly (loop) warns exactly once;
     - a guarded/never-evaluated occurrence warns zero times;
     - with the escalation knob on, the warning becomes the corresponding
       error and (only then) changes program outcome.
   Capture the emitted text so the message format is pinned.

6. Make the warnings actually visible. Since the user has never seen one,
   verify the output stream/sink the warnings go to is the one a normal
   `alfe`/clautolisp run surfaces, and that no verbosity/quiet default is
   swallowing them. Document how a user enables/sees them.

Out of scope
------------

- The static-analysis tool itself. This issue covers the run-time
  emitter and the shared catalogue; a static linter is a separate
  consumer of the same catalogue and can be a follow-up.
- Authoring the full construct catalogue in one pass — start with
  `&rest`, add entries incrementally as cross-vendor hazards are
  confirmed elsewhere.

Definition of done
-------------------

- The run-time dialect portability-warning mechanism exists and matches
  chapter 25: evaluation-tied, once-per-occurrence, advisory, dialect-
  gated.
- `defun` `&rest` warns per the spec under :strict / :autocad-2026 and is
  silent under :bricscad-v26 / :clautolisp.
- Tests validate the firing/dedup/guarded/escalation behaviours and pin
  the message text.
- Warnings are demonstrably visible in a normal run; how to see them is
  documented.
- DEVELOP bumped in tools/clautolisp/source/version.lisp.


Progress (branch fix-spec-pages, clautolisp 1.6.5)
--------------------------------------------------
DONE — the run-time mechanism now matches ch.25 for the &rest consumer:
  - Once-per-occurrence dedup: per-run table on the runtime-session,
    keyed by source occurrence (lambda-list cons identity). Loop warns
    once; distinct defuns warn independently; guarded/never-evaluated
    defun never warns (emit is evaluation-tied). New slot
    runtime-session-portability-warnings-seen in
    autolisp-runtime/source/model.lisp; helper
    %portability-warning-occurrence-seen-p in api.lisp.
  - Escalation knob: new :portability-warning-mode dialect-descriptor
    slot (default :warn) in autolisp-reader/source/dialect.lisp, exported
    accessor autolisp-dialect-portability-warning-mode; :error signals a
    :non-portable-construct AutoLISP runtime error (mirrors
    :unbound-variable-mode :strict-error), off by default.
  - Visibility: warnings go to *error-output* (stderr) — surfaced by a
    normal clautolisp/alfe run; documented on the emitter and in
    RELEASE_NOTES.
  - Tests (autolisp-runtime/tests/evaluator-tests.lisp): loop-warns-once,
    distinct-occurrences, guarded-silent, escalation-errors,
    default-mode-no-error. autolisp-runtime suite 355/355; full
    make test-sbcl 5293 checks, 0 failures. DEVELOP bumped to 1.6.5.

REMAINING (issue stays OPEN):
  - [pjb] Canonical message format. The emitter keeps the existing
    "[lambda-list-extension] …" text (pinned by the pre-existing
    variadic-warning tests). Spec ch.25 shows a *representative*
    "DIALECT WARNING: DEFUN FOO with &REST only works in bricscad and
    clautolisp" form. Deciding which is canonical — and whether to
    include the function name — is a pjb call, since switching the format
    means rewriting the existing tests. Not changed here.
  - Shared knowledge base / catalogue (DoD 2 "one knowledge base", DoD
    4 "enumerate other constructs"): only &rest is wired, coded inline
    (dialect-name case in emit-lambda-list-extension-warning). Factoring
    out a construct -> supporting-host/dialect + message catalogue, and
    walking ch.24 (BricsCAD Extensions) to populate it, is deferred — the
    issue itself asks to add entries incrementally as hazards are
    confirmed. The static-analysis consumer remains explicitly out of
    scope.
